a.org\/wiki\/Fractional_quantum_Hall_effect\" title=\"Fractional quantum Hall effect\">fractional quantum Hall effect<\/a>.<\/p><p>Laughlin was born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Visalia,_California\" title=\"Visalia, California\">Visalia, California<\/a>. He earned a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bachelor_of_Arts\" title=\"Bachelor of Arts\">B.A.<\/a> in Mathematics from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/UC_Berkeley\" title=\"UC Berkeley\" class=\"mw-redirect\">UC Berkeley<\/a> in 1972, and his <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Doctor_of_Philosophy\" title=\"Doctor of Philosophy\">Ph.D.<\/a> in physics in 1979 at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology\" title=\"Massachusetts Institute of Technology\">Massachusetts Institute of Technology<\/a> (MIT), <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cambridge,_Massachusetts\" title=\"Cambridge, Massachusetts\">Cambridge, Massachusetts<\/a>, USA. Between 2004 and 2006 he served as the president of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/KAIST\" title=\"KAIST\">KAIST<\/a> in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Daejeon\" title=\"Daejeon\">Daejeon<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/South_Korea\" title=\"South Korea\">South Korea<\/a>.<\/p><p>Laughlin shares similar views to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Chapline,_Jr.\" title=\"George Chapline, Jr.\">George Chapline<\/a>, doubting the existence of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Black_holes\" title=\"Black holes\" class=\"mw-redirect\">black holes<\/a>.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">[<i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (April 2012)\">citation needed<\/span><\/a><\/i>]<\/sup><\/p>","name":"Robert B. Laughlin","place_of_birth":"Visalia, California ,